# Performance Optimization

## Relationship to other rules

This rule supplements always-on agent rules; it does not override them.

- **Reviews:** Use as the Performance axis detail for `code-review-and-quality.mdc`.
- **Tests:** Do not run the full suite during routine dev unless the user asks — see `skip-tests-in-dev.mdc`.

## When to Use

- New or modified list/search endpoints
- Database query changes or new ORM relationships
- Loops over collections that trigger I/O
- UI components rendering lists or heavy computations
- New dependencies with bundle impact
- Any change flagged during the Performance axis of `code-review-and-quality`

## Review Workflow

### Step 1: Identify Hot Paths

Determine where the change runs frequently or at scale:

- Request handlers on high-traffic routes
- Render loops in UI components
- Background jobs processing batches
- Code inside tight loops over collections

### Step 2: Check Asymptotics

Ask: how does cost scale with input size?

| Pattern | Cost | Action |
|---------|------|--------|
| Single indexed query | O(1) per request | Usually fine |
| N+1 queries in loop | O(n) queries | **Critical** — fix with join/eager load |
| Unbounded fetch | O(all records) | **Critical** — add pagination |
| Re-render all children | O(components) per keystroke | Required if user-facing |

### Step 3: Quantify When Possible

Prefer measurable statements over vague concerns:

- "This adds 1 query per item — ~50ms × 100 items = ~5s" beats "this might be slow"
- "Bundle adds 45KB gzipped" beats "large dependency"
- "Renders 2000 DOM nodes" beats "might lag"

### Step 4: Run the Checklist

Work through [performance-checklist.md](../references/performance-checklist.md). Flag findings with severity labels from `code-review-and-quality`:

| Prefix | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| **Critical:** | Blocks merge — unbounded ops, N+1 on hot path |
| *(no prefix)* | Required — must fix before merge |
| **Nit:** | Minor — low-traffic path, negligible impact |
| **Optional:** / **Consider:** | Suggestion — premature optimization risk |

## When to Profile

| Checklist finding | Profile? |
|-------------------|----------|
| Obvious N+1 or missing pagination | No — fix directly |
| Latency complaint without clear cause | Yes — measure first |
| Complex aggregation query | Yes — benchmark with realistic volume |
| UI jank | Yes — browser profiler or React DevTools |

**Rule:** Don't optimize without a measured bottleneck unless the checklist finding is structurally obvious (N+1, unbounded fetch).

## Common Misses

| Miss | Impact |
|------|--------|
| Pagination added to API but not UI | Frontend still fetches everything |
| Eager loading entire relation graph | Over-fetching replaces N+1 with one huge query |
| Caching without invalidation | Stale data bugs |
| Memoization everywhere | Added complexity without measured benefit |
| Sync I/O in async handler | Blocks event loop under load |

## Output Format

```markdown
## Performance Review: [change title]

### Hot paths affected
- [list paths and expected frequency]

### Findings
- **Critical:** [finding] — [file:line] — [estimated impact]
- [Required finding] — [file:line]
- **Consider:** [suggestion]

### Profiling performed
- [ ] Not needed — structural issue identified
- [ ] Benchmarked: [method, result]

### Verdict
- [ ] Approve (no Critical/Required findings)
- [ ] Request changes
```

